{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638585"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:57:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:57:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17724"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17724"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10438"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72299"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10438"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17724"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57769"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10183"},{"type":"tags","id":"10187"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24480"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72299"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe proliferative phase is a critical stage in wound healing that typically begins around day three after injury and can last for several weeks.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary cellular events during the proliferative phase of wound healing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Keratinocyte differentiation and cornification","Mast cell degranulation and histamine release","Fibroblast activation and collagen deposition","Neutrophil infiltration and bacterial clearance","Platelet aggregation and clot formation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efibroblast activation and collagen deposition\u003C/strong\u003E are the hallmark features of the proliferative phase of wound healing. During this phase, fibroblasts migrate into the wound site and produce collagen and other extracellular matrix components. This process is accompanied by angiogenesis, forming granulation tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutrophil infiltration and bacterial clearance\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during the inflammatory phase, which precedes the proliferative phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelet aggregation and clot formation\u003C/strong\u003E characterise the immediate haemostatic phase following injury\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMast cell degranulation and histamine release\u003C/strong\u003E are early inflammatory events that occur shortly after injury\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeratinocyte differentiation and cornification\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily associated with the later remodelling phase of wound healing\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe proliferative phase is essential for wound closure and restoration of tissue integrity. It involves the formation of granulation tissue, which consists of new blood vessels, fibroblasts, and the extracellular matrix they produce.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The proliferative phase of wound healing is characterised by fibroblast activity, angiogenesis, and granulation tissue formation.","Fibroblasts produce collagen and extracellular matrix components during the proliferative phase.","New blood vessel formation (angiogenesis) is essential for delivering oxygen and nutrients to healing tissue."],"refere